<subSubSection id="DDBD6569FFF905618993FF54E11D15D9" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="951836E2FFF905618993FF54E11D15D9" blockId="45.[151,1436,151,429]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis id="A7D3EAF0FFF905618993FF54E44E14C5" bold="true" box="[199,335,151,176]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">Comments.</emphasis>
As the female 
<typeStatus id="4A1C8840FFF9056188ACFF5BE72914C5" box="[504,552,152,176]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">type</typeStatus>
is currently lost, our recombination is based only on the original description of 
<bibRefCitation id="F1364B13FFF9056189C3FF7FE42914A1" author="Bigot, J. M. F." box="[151,296,188,213]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" pagination="183 - 208" refId="ref21580" refString="Bigot, J. M. F. (1879) Dipteres nouveaux ou peu connus. 11 e partie. XVI. Curiae Xylophagidarum et Stratiomydarum (Bigot) [part]. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, Cinquieme Serie, 9, 183 - 208." type="journal article" year="1879">Bigot (1879)</bibRefCitation>
, who mostly described coloration. The species is mostly yellow, except the vertex and upper frons that are dark metallic blue, the wings are grey, and the abdominal fourth and fifth segments are dark brown with metallic purple reflections. The abdomen was described by 
<bibRefCitation id="F1364B13FFF905618A09FEC7E6F31569" author="Bigot, J. M. F." box="[861,1010,260,285]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" pagination="183 - 208" refId="ref21580" refString="Bigot, J. M. F. (1879) Dipteres nouveaux ou peu connus. 11 e partie. XVI. Curiae Xylophagidarum et Stratiomydarum (Bigot) [part]. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, Cinquieme Serie, 9, 183 - 208." type="journal article" year="1879">Bigot (1879)</bibRefCitation>
as being metallic purple with three transverse triangular yellow maculae at the base (probably the first segment). It is likely that this species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="52A74D61FFF90561885EFE8FE46D1511" baseAuthorityName="Williston" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[266,364,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Sargus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">
<emphasis id="A7D3EAF0FFF90561885EFE8FE46D1511" box="[266,364,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">S. analis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="52A74D61FFF9056188F1FE8FE7351511" authorityName="Lindner" authorityYear="1928" box="[421,564,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Sargus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavoniger">
<emphasis id="A7D3EAF0FFF9056188F1FE8FE7351511" box="[421,564,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">S. flavoniger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, or possibly even related to 
<taxonomicName id="52A74D61FFF905618A2DFE8FE6F91511" authorityName="Fachin &amp; Hauser" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Schiner" baseAuthorityYear="1868" box="[889,1016,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Chrysonotus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dichrous">
<emphasis id="A7D3EAF0FFF905618A2DFE8FE6F91511" box="[889,1016,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">S. dichrous</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of its metallic abdomen. As this description appears to most reliably place the species in 
<taxonomicName id="52A74D61FFF905618A3AFEB3E6BB15F2" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[878,954,368,391]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Sargus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A7D3EAF0FFF905618A3AFEB3E6BB15F2" box="[878,954,368,391]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">Sargus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it will be transferred there until further material is available, but this color pattern clearly excludes it from 
<taxonomicName id="52A74D61FFF905618AD2FE56E11415D9" authorityName="James in James &amp; McFadden" authorityYear="1982" box="[902,1045,405,428]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Himantigera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A7D3EAF0FFF905618AD2FE56E11415D9" box="[902,1045,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">Himantigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
